[[File:Korizu-jinja torii-2.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Torii}}]]
'''Korizu Shrine''' (こおりずじんじゃ<ref name="説明板"/>) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Kamobe Kamimachi, {{ill|lt=Kōchi|Q200251|qid=Q200251|1=Kōchi, Kōchi}}, {{ill|lt=Kōchi Prefecture|Q134093|qid=Q134093|1=Kōchi Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, and its former rank under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=old ranking|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deity ===
The shrine enshrines one deity<ref name="説明板">Precinct information board.</ref>:
* {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|qid=Q276944|lt=Ōkuninushi-no-Kami|1=Ōkuninushi}}

=== History ===
[[File:Korizu-jinja honden-2.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Honden}}]]
=== Founding ===
The founding date is unknown{{Sfn|郡頭神社（式内社）|1987}}. In the '{{ill|lt=Shoku Nihongi|Q611399|qid=Q611399|1=Shoku Nihongi}}' entry for {{ill|lt=Jingo-keiun|Q1373049|qid=Q1373049|1=Jingo-keiun}} 2 ({{ill|lt=768|Q29961|qid=Q29961|1=768}}), 11th month, 18th day, it records that 41 people including Kamiyoda no Sukuna from Tosa District, Tosa Province, were granted the surname "{{ill|lt=Kamo no Ason clan|Q122979457|qid=Q122979457|lt=Kamo|1=Kamo no Ason clan}}"; "Kamiyoda" is said to refer to the nearby place name Kōda{{Sfn|郡頭神社（式内社）|1987}}. Also, in '{{ill|lt=Shinsen Shōjiroku|Q1045362|qid=Q1045362|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku}}' under Settsu Province, divine lineage, Chigi, Kamo-be-hafuri entry, it says: "Kamo-be-hafuri, same ancestor as Kamo no Ason, descendants of Ōkuninushi"{{Sfn|郡頭神社（式内社）|1987}}. From these records, it is said this shrine began when Kamo/Kamobe groups (be-min of the Kamo clan) living around Kamobe enshrined Ōkuninushi as ancestral deity{{Sfn|郡頭神社（式内社）|1987}}{{Sfn|郡頭神社（平凡社）|1983}}.

This area is identified with Kamobe-gō of Tosa District in the '{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Wamyōshō|1=UNKNOWN}}'{{Sfn|郡頭神社（式内社）|1987}}. Development of Kamobe-gō is seen as from the {{ill|lt=Kofun period|Q459939|qid=Q459939|1=Kofun period}}, and primitive rituals are inferred by around the {{ill|lt=6th century|Q8090|qid=Q8090|1=6th century}}{{Sfn|郡頭神社（式内社）|1987}}. Later prosperity is seen in a Tōdaiji document: in {{ill|lt=Tenpyō-shōhō|Q1373169|qid=Q1373169|1=Tenpyō-shōhō}} 4 ({{ill|lt=752|Q23639|qid=Q23639|1=752}}), 50 households from Kamobe-gō were assigned as {{ill|lt=fuko|Q11458391|qid=Q11458391|1=Fūko}} of {{ill|lt=Tōdai-ji|Q460367|qid=Q460367|1=Tōdai-ji}}{{Sfn|郡頭神社（式内社）|1987}}.

The shrine name "Korigashira/Koorizu" has unclear origin: theories include that it stands in Tosa District, the head district of Tosa Province; that district headquarters stood in Kamobe-gō; or that it derives from the place name Kōda{{Sfn|郡頭神社（式内社）|1987}}.

=== Overview history ===
In the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}' {{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} compiled in {{ill|lt=Enchō|Q1327274|qid=Q1327274|1=Enchō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|qid=Q30470|1=927}}), "Korizu Shrine" is listed in Tosa District, {{ill|lt=Tosa Province|Q857330|qid=Q857330|1=Tosa Province}}, identified with this shrine{{Sfn|郡頭神社（式内社）|1987}}. The reading there is given as "Kohoritsuno"{{Sfn|郡頭神社（式内社）|1987}}.

Later history is unclear, but ridge tags from {{ill|lt=Eishō|Q1193577|qid=Q1193577|1=Eishō (Muromachi period)}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1504|Q6148|qid=Q6148|1=1504}}) and {{ill|lt=Kan'ei|Q1192913|qid=Q1192913|1=Kan'ei}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1708|Q6846|qid=Q6846|1=1708}}) suggest that from the {{ill|lt=medieval period|Q12554|qid=Q12554|1=Middle Ages}} onward the common shrine name became "Kamobe Shrine"{{Sfn|郡頭神社（式内社）|1987}}.

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|qid=Q7753|1=1872}}), it was ranked {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}} in the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}<ref name="説明板"/>. In {{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 56 ({{ill|lt=1981|Q2437|qid=Q2437|1=1981}}), a fire destroyed the shrine buildings; the current buildings are rebuilt afterward<ref name="説明板"/>.

